 themselves relied on faulty translations based on oral traditions. Xuanzang may have encountered a similar situation, or may have taken the supposed content of the inscriptions from Faxian's writings. This theory is corroborated by the fact that some Brahmin scholars are known to have similarly come up with a fanciful interpretation of Ashoka pillar inscriptions, when requested to decipher them by the 14th century Muslim king Firuz Shah Tughlaq. According to Shams-i Siraj's Tarikh-i Firoz Shahi, after the king had these pillar transported from Topra and Mirat to Delhi as war trophies, these Brahmins told him that the inscriptions prophesied that nobody would be able to remove the pillars except a king named Firuz. Moreover, by this time, there were local traditions that attributed the erection of these pillars to the legendary hero Bhima.", "annotations": [{"surface": "Ashokavadana", "start": 118, "end": 130, "uri": "https://calvoritmo.com/tfm/entity/0a72f48e-3181-4fdf-b95c-d4e6b216843e", "source": "i"}, {"surface": "Firuz Shah Tughlaq", "start": 1345, "end": 1363, "uri": "http://dbpedia.org/resource/Firuz_Shah_Tughlaq", "source": "a"}, {"surface": "Tarikh-i Firoz Shahi", "start": 1394, "end": 1414, "uri": "https://calvoritmo.com/tfm/entity/4dcdc728-5c8c-4747-b1e1-c9b31cdd92c1", "source": "i"}, {"surface": "Topra", "start": 1465, "end": 1470, "uri": "http://dbpedia.org/resource/Topra_Kalan", "source": "a"}, {"surface": "Bhima", "start": 1759, "end": 1764, "uri": "http://dbpedia.org/resource/Bhima", "source": "a"}, {"surface": "Ashoka", "start": 27, "end": 33, "uri": "http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ashoka", "source": "dbpedia_spotlight"}, {"surface": "Buddhist", "start": 48, "end": 56, "uri": "http://dbpedia.org/resource/Buddhism", "source": "dbpedia_spotlight"}, {"surface": "Ashokavadana", "start": 118, "end": 130, "uri": "http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ashokavadana", "source": "dbpedia_spotlight"}, {"surface": "rock", "start": 148, "end": 152, "uri": "http://dbpedia.org